9wtUXFSYKfxC_AFQuLvSQglnf2gbdkrv2F2vUP1cM6TuRrQ3aoIvqIk0heRt-iWUPvg4Mx4DEQM0WQHSfmUGXgq6SfTEKfyhx01WFwbdSZqvJH5s984qKzZ5anVx6Nt427UUkuGnQAA1Z_KvnDgoO3FtWE5olb7P2rj_wVzlS2IUl7PGyJfEcbhCDvEWILX6JBPIzfpvthJJ5hEL4tK1t1_8DNRsj2z9E2jD4N6NUD73dzaQgoGSdJyyCc_J8TgwYiT6QAOHJfj3ipEPjhG_sKj2PQ9nQPA4ioHH3deWdzeJDgy5s9fUnMrSNnrLBIbjEm2hPrKrJvzai0apMWDUir5bKEL1S-1t2XumeXWYB2fcw4j38QNyah74TtvhBOh7BDzBvo_MlahlxFhT5KNvPBWMo9BVWvxep9sWyOu4jS2w10LGy-65fy4xrz-Bs9QCPVjeFb37FWW0SnwZSboPJ-64oYDIt5SuTcV98Bc7ZVOWcv6EK5YSNvk9rlRgLTLcpOUzJEXt4ZnTntTO56dNdYCXW_PwYHq8ZdUfVlI16F_0zinP2pQf_cJ8t0c5Fi_pUS4cbFgQgwEO9hDMROn1z5_4BWZJvfwtskt2vNcovUbfXrIfbZbez-CDbcsjxBCHRgV87hxxPNTZQD33q4LQzFFNGaRGQPWC0I4OJ_ZuUEqZxaMqkzfJhKqH8T2CAGwTPstP1k8BH6PRfTb4nF27zfHpIEif9sTzN8Je473dzs_Xts_hj5DoEksir5MMA1FAPdroJ-jjvbbXpuMOo67dUj-dyTATErQz_K8ARoSO6jRfjr46g-ZRztO_hzR45EWvsP88V5jpdQXX_L2F1fzjD6pRcijOyvedi9_znKtuFLE4DA4NY=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Implementing Proxy Annotations**\\n\\nI need to work on the implementation by adding annotations on abstract superclasses. For the package-private abstract class `ProxyFactoryManualProxySuperclass`, I'll use `@ProxyFor(ProxyFactorySampleService.class)` and possibly `@ProxyResult(MANUAL)`. I'll also need to include abstract methods for getting and setting delegates. For caching with `ProxyAccess`, I'll annotate with `@ProxyAccess(ProxyFactoryProxyAccess.class)`, ensuring its value is an interface with a specific getter and setter pattern. My next step involves managing the proxy classes and ensuring the names are generated correctly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Generating Proxy Class Names**\\n\\nI'm working on the class name format, which is a combination of the package, superclass name, interface name, and specific encoding using special characters. The goal is to prevent nesting by using top-level helpers, while ensuring the package name remains unaffected by underscores. The Java class identifier seems fine even with characters 